revision.text:
{{also|Jump}}
==English==
===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK|US}} {{enPR|jŭmp}}, {{IPA|en|/dʒʌmp/|[d͡ʒʌmp]}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-jump.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ʌmp|s=1}}
===Etymology 1===
[[File:NwFusionTapM.jpg|thumb|125px|A tap dancer jumping.]]
From {{inh|en|enm|jumpen|t=to walk quickly, run, jump}}, probably of {{der|en|gml|-}} or {{der|en|gmq|-}} origin, ultimately from {{der|en|gem-pro|*gempaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*gembaną|t=to hop, skip, jump}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*gʷʰemb-|t=to spring, hop, jump}}.  The OED instead suggests an {{onomatopoeic|en|title=imitative}} origin.<ref>{{R:OED}}</ref> Related to {{l|en|jumble}}.
{{rel-top|Cognates}}
Cognate with {{cog|dum|gumpen||to jump}}, {{cog|nds|jumpen||to jump}}, {{cog|gmh|gumpen}}, {{m|gmh|gampen||to jump, hop}} (dialectal {{cog|de|gampen}}, {{cog|gsw|gumpe}}, [[Walser]] dialect {{m|de|kumpu}}), {{cog|da|gumpe||to jolt}}, {{cog|sv|gumpa||to jump}}, {{cog|da|gimpe||to move up and down}}, {{cog|enm|jumpren}}, {{m|enm|jumbren||to mix, jumble}}. {{rel-bottom}}
====Verb====
{{en-verb}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[propel]] oneself [[rapidly]] [[upward]], [[downward]] and/or in any horizontal direction such that [[momentum]] causes the [[body]] to become [[airborne]].
#: {{ux|en|The boy '''jumped''' over a fence.}}
#: {{ux|en|Kangaroos are known for their ability to '''jump''' high.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Winter's Tale|IV|iv|passage=Not the worst of the three but '''jumps''' twelve foot and a half by the square.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To cause oneself to [[leave]] an [[elevated]] location and fall [[downward]].
#: {{ux|en|She is going to '''jump''' from the diving board.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To pass by a spring or leap; to overleap.
#: {{ux|en|to '''jump''' a stream}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To employ a [[parachute]] to leave an [[aircraft]] or elevated location.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To react to a [[sudden]], often [[unexpected]], [[stimulus]] (such as a [[sharp]] [[prick]] or a loud sound) by [[jerk]]ing the body [[violently]].
#: {{ux|en|The sudden sharp sound made me '''jump'''.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|figuratively}} To [[increase]] sharply, to [[rise]], to [[shoot up]].
#: {{ux|en|Share prices '''jumped''' by 10% after the company announced record profits.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To employ a [[move]] in certain [[board games]] where one game piece is moved from one legal [[position]] to another [[pass]]ing over the position of another piece.
#: {{ux|en|The player's knight '''jumped''' the opponent's bishop.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To move to a position (in a [[queue]]/[[line]]) that is further forward.
#: {{ux|en|I hate it when people '''jump''' the queue.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[attack]] suddenly and violently.
#: {{ux|en|The hoodlum '''jumped''' a woman in the alley.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|slang}} To engage in [[sexual intercourse]] with (a person).
#* '''1983''', ''[[w:The Big Chill (film)|The Big Chill]]'':
#*: Harold: How is Sarah? I don't want to '''jump''' her while she's [[on the rag]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cause]] to jump.
#: {{ux|en|The rider '''jumped''' the horse over the fence.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To move the distance between two opposing subjects.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To increase the [[height]] of a [[tower crane]] by inserting a section at the base of the tower and jacking up everything above it.
# {{lb|en|cycling|intransitive}} To [[increase]] [[speed]] aggressively and without warning.
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To expose to danger; to risk; to hazard.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Coriolanus|III|i|passage=to '''jump''' a body with a dangerous physic}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|smithwork}} To join by a [[buttweld]].
# To [[thicken]] or [[enlarge]] by [[endwise]] [[blows]]; to [[upset]].
# {{lb|en|quarrying}} To [[bore]] with a [[jumper]].
# To [[jump-start]] a car or other vehicle with a dead [[battery]], as with [[jumper cable]]s.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2000|author=United States. Employees' Compensation Appeals Board|title=Decisions of the Employees' Compensation Appeals Board: Index digest|page=511
|text=[Someone] and Mr. Benfield were at the corner of Elm and Walton Streets when they were approached by Mr. Gray, who asked for help to '''jump''' his car. When informed they did not have jumper cables, Mr. Gray asked them to take him to get some.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2015-01-30|author=Robert M. Morgan|author2=Janet Turner Parish|author3=George Deitz|title=Handbook on Research in Relationship Marketing|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|isbn=9781783478637|page=250
|text={{...}} his wife, who was at home with their children, would drive to school to '''jump''' his car; both would drive home;{{nb...}}}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To coincide; to agree; to accord; to tally; followed by ''with''.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=William Shakespeare |authorlink=William Shakespeare|title=Henry IV, Part 1|year=a. 1597|section=Act I, scene ii|text=It '''jumps''' with my humour.}}
#*:
# {{lb|en|intransitive|programming}} To start [[execute|executing]] [[code]] from a different [[location]], rather than following the [[program counter]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=Garry Robinson|title=Real World Microsoft Access Database Protection and Security|passage=When this section is completed, the code generally '''jumps''' back to the Exit Section, and the procedure is closed.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|slang|archaic}} To [[flee]]; to make one's escape.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1891|author=Arthur Conan Doyle|title=The Red-Headed League|passage=“It's all clear,” he whispered. “Have you the chisel and the bags? Great Scott! '''Jump''', Archie, '''jump''', and I'll swing for it!”<br>Sherlock Holmes had sprung out and seized the intruder by the collar. The other dived down the hole, and I heard the sound of rending cloth as Jones clutched at his skirts.}}
